Text = new Array();
Text[0]='INFORMAL commands: Indirect commands to direct commands <br />The subjunctive is used frequently to communicate one\'s wishes. When you want someone to do something your way, use the subjunctive as an "indirect command". For example, one can suggest, demand, and hope that the listener does what they ask (e.g. We hope that you get a job). When you want to order someone to do something in a more direct manner, use direct commands. Look at the three examples below and notice the difference. The indirect commands are more like suggestions. The direct commands are stronger. <br /><br />Indirect command----------------------------------------------------Direct command<br />I want you to clean your room.----------------------------------Clean your room!<br />We prefer that you study your math.-------------------------Study your math!<br />I suggest that you put on your shoes.-----------------------Put on your shoes! <br /><br /><br />Formation:<br />Commands are broken down into affirmative (do this, do that) and negative (don\'t do this, don\'t do that). There are separate formations for affirmative and negative t\u00FA commands. In most cases, the affirmative t\u00FA command looks just like the 3rd person indicative. Have a look at a traditional verb conjugation such as HABLAR:<br />Hablo<br />Hablas<br />Habla---Add the exclamation mark and you have the informal command: Habla! (Speak!)<br /><br />Similarly, <br />Leo<br />Lees<br />Lee---Add the exclamation mark and you have the informal command: Lee! (Read!)<br /><br />On the other hand, negative t\u00FA commands look exactly like the second person subjunctive, so the formation is based on the YO of the present indicative. Start with the YO (hablo, como vivo, tengo) and drop the O. You are now left with habl, com, viv, teng.<br /><br />For AR verbs add the following endings: ES <br />For ER/IR verbs add these endings: AS<br /><br />For example-Comer: No comas! (Do not eat!) <br /> Hablar: No hables! (Do not speak!)<br /><br />OJO! OJO! OJO! Any kind of pronoun (indirect, direct, or reflexive) MUST be at the end of an affirmative command (eg. Si\u00E9ntaTE, Lev\u00E1ntaTE, and BEFORE the negative command (eg. No TE sientes, No TE levantes).<br /><br />In the exercise that follows, change the statement from indirect commands (mere suggestions) to direct INFORMAL (t\u00FA) commands.<br /><br />Yo quiero que t\u00FA pagues la cuenta. <br />';
